                     <div id="comment-27243" class="issue-data-block activity-comment twixi-block expanded">
    <div class="twixi-wrap verbose actionContainer">
        <a href="#" class="twixi"><span class="icon twixi-opened"><span>Hide</span></span></a>
        <div class="action-links">
            <a href="/browse/SHBL-24?focusedCommentId=27243&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-27243" title="A permanent link to this comment." class="icon icon-perma"><span>Permalink</span></a>
                                </div>
        <div class="action-details">
    
    
    
                

    <a class="user-hover user-avatar" rel="gswduke" style="background-image:url(/secure/useravatar?size=small&amp;avatarId=10182);"  id="commentauthor_27243_verbose" href="/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=gswduke">Gary S. Weaver</a>
 added a comment  - <span class='commentdate_27243_verbose subText'><span class='date user-tz' title='21/Aug/09 8:42 AM'><time datetime='2009-08-21T08:42-0700'>21/Aug/09 8:42 AM</time></span></span>  </div>
        <div class="action-body flooded"><p>Erkki,</p>

<p>I hear what you are saying, but I think I'm not being clear as to what I'm saying which is that Shibboleth (not the authenticator) as far as I know can only guard parts of a website. How this fits into Confluence is that Shibboleth can guard the part of the Confluence site that is used to Login in place of Confluence's own Login form, and therefore there is no ability to Login as a Confluence user if you do that, because there is no place for you to enter your Confluence username and password- only a place to enter your username and password into whatever Shibboleth is using as the Login form.</p>

<p>So as far as I know, even though nothing is stopping you from Confluence using various user repositories under the hood with the Confluence API (this authenticator is not stopping you from doing that), the whole point of the Shibboleth authenticator is that you would have logged in via Shibboleth, and Shibboleth is passing a REMOTE_USER HTTP Header from the Shibboleth SP (local on the server) after the user logs in via Shibboleth, and the Shibboleth authenticator is then using that REMOTE_USER HTTP Header as an authoritative source for the Confluence username. There should be no way for the user to login any other way as far as I know.</p>

<p>I'm sure that I am really not understanding what your previous setup was and what has been done in your environment to keep you from doing what you did before, so I look forward to your response or to hearing more from Juhani.</p>

<p>Let me repeat one final time: nothing that I know of was done in the Shibboleth authenticator that could have stopped you from doing anything that you could have in earlier versions of the authenticator related to login. If the issue is that you were not using the Shibboleth authenticator before but rather something that was homegrown that had the ability to not only check REMOTE_USER but existing username and password in the Confluence DB somehow, then we'd be more than happy to add that option into the authenticator as an option if you could provide that code and it is something that would be useful to others.</p>

<p>Thanks,<br/>
Gary</p> </div>
    </div>
